{
  "format": "wspradar.config",
  "schema_version": 1,
  "profile": {
    "id": "milazzo_tx_buddy",
    "title": {
      "en": "Dr. Milazzo Revisited: Extending an Early Multi-Part WSPR Antenna Study with Same-Cycle Evidence"
    },
    "description": {
      "en": "[Technical article: Milazzo, C. F. / KP4MD (2011). Using the Weak Signal Propagation Reporter Network to Compare Antenna Performance](https://www.qsl.net/kp4md/wspr.htm)\n\n Milazzo’s work is one of the early detailed operator-led WSPR antenna studies, combining 40 m and 20 m transmit comparisons at VE6PDQ, reciprocal receive observations, and checks against VOACAP propagation predictions. This demo revisits one part—the 40 m KP4MD full-wave loop versus WB6RQN GAP Titan DX transmit comparison—and extends it from VE6PDQ to all reporting receivers while applying reported-power normalization, the Target-Active Gate, and same-cycle pairing. The gated evidence preserves the expected reach and operating-pattern asymmetry: 1,093 Only-KP4MD versus 21 Only-WB6RQN peer-cycles, with the underlying non-joint KP4MD reports—including VE6PDQ’s 62 target-only records—available for validation in Drill-Down. Because KP4MD operated continuously while WB6RQN frequency-hopped, those non-joint reports cannot isolate antenna performance; the narrower synchronized subset contains 46 joint reports from nine shared cycles and has median ΔSNR (KP4MD loop − WB6RQN GAP Titan DX) ≈ −4 dB. Together, these complementary views preserve the value of the original study while demonstrating why operating schedules, gating, non-joint evidence, and synchronized comparisons must be interpreted separately."
    }
  },
